Then, anti-GPC1/AuNCs/GO/AuE was used for the quantitative determination of GPC1. As shown in Fig. 3E, the photocurrent gradually declined as the concentration of GPC1 increased. The photocurrent change (ΔI = I – I

                              0
                           ) was directly proportional to the logarithm of GPC1 concentration (inset in Fig. 3E). The slope of this line was defined as the sensitivity of the sensor. According to this working curve, a detection limit of 3.33 ng/mL (S/N = 3) can be obtained. According to the literature, the LOD of the PEC immunosensor can satisfy the requirement for the detection of pancreatic cancer patients, of which the average concentration of GPC1 was 2.56 ng/mL [16,47,48]. However, the concentration of GPC1 in blood from early pancreatic cancer patients can be much lower. Therefore, the sensing properties of the anti-GPC1/AuNCs/GO/AuE PEC sensor need to be further improved to meet the measurement requirements of early diagnosis pancreatic cancer.
